<P>
DALEY PROPOSES NEW AIRPORT FOR CHICAGO 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Staff and Wire Reports 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Mayor Richard M. Daley proposed building a $4.9-billion, 9,400-acre airport in 
the Lake Calumet area on Chicago's Southeast Side, to be operational by 2010. 
The site includes hazardous waste areas and about 5,500 residences. Rep. Henry 
J. Hyde (R-Ill.), who prefers to expand O'Hare International Airport, 
criticized Daley's cost figures as too low. State and federal officials and 
residents of the area around O'Hare have been promoting the idea of a new 
Chicago airport to relieve congestion at O'Hare. U.S. Transportation Secretary 
Samuel K. Skinner endorsed the Daley plan. 
