<HEADLINE>
<P>
DEBRIS KICKED UP BY TRUCK BLAMED FOR DEATH ON FREEWAY 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By CHARISSE JONES, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
An object that killed a Harbor Freeway motorist earlier this week and raised 
suspicions that the man had been murdered by a missile tossed from an overpass 
in fact was a piece of debris kicked up by a truck's tires, authorities said 
Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
"It was just a freak accident," Los Angeles Police Detective Erin Browne said 
of the incident that killed 34-year-old John A. Raff as he traveled past the 
Harbor Freeway's 23rd Street overpass early Tuesday afternoon. 
</P>
<P>
Raff, a Los Angeles resident and self-employed glass architect, was southbound 
in his van when a truck traveling in front of him apparently kicked up the 
metal base of a street sign lying in the roadway, propelling the object through 
Raff's windshield, Browne said. 
</P>
<P>
Homicide investigators initially were assigned to the case because it was 
unclear whether the object that killed Raff had been thrown from the overpass 
or hurled up from the roadway. 
</P>
<P>
However, Browne said, "we found pieces of what resembled a metal disk that is 
the base of (a) stop sign . . . along the freeway" and determined that it was 
responsible for the accident. Officials said that calls from witnesses also 
helped in the investigation. 
</P>
<P>
Raff, whose van came to rest against a freeway center divider just south of 
Adams Boulevard, died at the scene. 
</P>
<P>
An autopsy, completed Thursday afternoon, concluded that he had died of cranial 
cerebral trauma, according to Bob Dambacher, spokesman for the Los Angeles 
County coroner's office. 
</P>
<P>
Caltrans spokeswoman Margie Tiritilli would not comment on the incident, but 
said that the state agency in charge of California's highway system makes a 
concerted effort to keep roadways clear of debris. 
</P>
<P>
"It's part of our maintenance program," said Tiritilli, explaining that agency 
employees regularly patrol the freeways, as well as respond to calls from 
motorists and California Highway Patrol officers who have spotted potentially 
hazardous objects on the roadway. 
</P>
<P>
"It's an ongoing, constant thing," she said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
