<HEADLINE>
<P>
IN CONCERT 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By MARISSA ROTH 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
It was another scene entirely at the Laurie Anderson concert, across town at 
the Wiltern Theatre. The general fashion effect was minimalist. 
</P>
<P>
Many outfits looked as if they had been layered together after random visits to 
thrift shops. There was little glamour and no glitz, but one definite surprise 
-- a man in an ankle-grazing velvet skirt worn with a dinner jacket. Plenty of 
men, as well as women, wore black leather jackets (Anderson, a performance 
artist-turned-professional musician, often wears one, too) or flowing duster 
coats. But some accessorized with splashes of color. A saffron vest, a ginger 
scarf, cappuccino lipstick or cinnamon-tinted hosiery were reminders that such 
tones do exist, even at rock concerts. Lots of hats, especially bowlers, topped 
off this solemnly chic crowd. MARISSA ROTH 
</P>
</TEXT>
