<HEADLINE>
<P>
P. M. BRIEFING; 
</P>
<P>
CANADA'S TRADE SURPLUS SHRINKS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Reuters 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
OTTAWA 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A robust currency and weakening U.S. economic growth shrank Canada's 
merchandise trade surplus last year to its lowest level in a decade, a federal 
agency said today. 
</P>
<P>
Canada's exports grew 1.2% in 1989 while imports climbed a more brisk 5.3% for 
a net trade surplus of $4.7 billion ($3.9 billion U.S.). 
</P>
<P>
That was less than half the $9.8 billion ($8.1 billion U.S.) surplus reported 
in 1988 when the Conservative government signed the free trade agreement with 
the United States, promising it would be a boon to business. The pact removed 
remaining tariffs on goods between the nations over 10 years. 
</P>
<P>
International Trade Minister John Crosbie has been under attack from opposition 
parties, which opposed free trade, for Canada's deteriorating trade position. 
</P>
<P>
A higher Canadian dollar made exports less attractive abroad last year while 
slashing the cost of such basic imports as clothing. 
</P>
</TEXT>
