<P>
BIOGRAPHY GETS MUSIC BOOK PRIZE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Staff and Wire Service Reports 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
NEW YORK 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
"Standing in the Shadows of Motown: The Life and Music of Legendary Bassist 
James Jamerson," a biography and song book by Allan Slutsky today was awarded 
the top prize in the Ralph J. Gleason Music Book Awards. 
</P>
<P>
This is the first of the yearly awards, named for the acclaimed jazz critic who 
co-founded Rolling Stone magazine, that will honor the year's best book about 
music or musicians. The awards are sponsored by Rolling Stone, music licensing 
giant BMI and New York University. 
</P>
<P>
Second place went to "Country: The Music and the Musicians," by the Country 
Music Foundation, edited by Paul Kingsbury and Alan Axelrod. Gunther Schuller's 
"The Swing Era: The Development of Jazz 1930-1945," was third. 
</P>
</TEXT>
